    BIG Problems with Quality this year

    Dear Libby's, We have been using your 29 ounce cans for our annual Thanksgiving fundraiser bake for a decade and make hundreds of pumpkin cranberry loaves and pumpkin pies every year. Our patrons counts on our pumpkin-based products to be excellent. This year we were extremely disappointed. Many of the cans we opened had a strange color and texture, and there was a small dark brown dot on the inner top of the can, as though the pumpkin has shrunk away too far in canning. We had to discard many cans and purchase new cans; some were OK, some were not. Some had expiration dates of October 2019, some November 2019 and when we replaced the pumpkin we bought from a different store just to make sure it wasn't an aberration. At first we thought, "it must be us", but then I looked here at other comments and realized that there have been many issues this year. We are really disappointed that the brand we trust (Libby's) did not do the essential quality control on its end. We would like to know how we can ensure quality moving forward. We generally love the consistency of Libby's product, which is why this was extra surprising.

    1. Response from nestlebaking:

      Libby's® Brand Ambassador
      · a year ago  

      Thanks for sharing your experience and photos. The discoloration you're describing may be due to the cooking process. After the cans are filled and sealed, the pumpkin is cooked at high temperatures to achieve commercial sterility. On rare occasions, some product may discolor slightly or burn on the inside of the lid or in the center of the pumpkin during the cooking process. Expect an email from us shortly.

    Disappointed last 3 cans

    I have baked with Libby's pumpkin for 50 years. The last time I purchased your canned pumpkin, I brought home 4 cans. I had very diconcerting, diappointing results with the first 3 cans. A pumpkin pie, pumpkin cheesecake, & a pumpkin pie bar recipe all contained a lot of sand. It was mortifying to serve sand to my family & friends. I went online & learned that these experiences have been widespread among other bakers. I threw out the last can, bought 5 pie pumpkins, & pressure-canned my own pumpkin. One pie made so far... perfection! I shall never again buy your canned pumpkin. If I can process pumpkins with no grit, you should be able to, as well.

    Originally posted on VeryBestBaking.com

This is not what we want you to expect from us and we'd like to report this to our team. Expect an email from us shortly.
